<div class="penelope">
  <img src="/img/welcomingcat.png" alt="Penelope the Neocities cat">
  <div class="penelope-Bubble">
    <p>One last trick, and it's the fun one: let's paint the place!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<p>HTML describes what's <em>on</em> your page. How it <em>looks</em> &mdash; colors, fonts, layouts &mdash; is the job of a second language called <strong>CSS</strong>. CSS is a whole adventure of its own, but here's a taste right now.</p>

<p>CSS lives inside a <code><%= '<style>' %></code> element in your page's <code><%= '<head>' %></code> &mdash; remember, the invisible part. This rule tells the browser: <em>make the body's background light sky blue</em>:</p>

<pre><code class="html"><%= "<style>\n  body {\n    background-color: lightskyblue;\n  }\n</style>" %></code></pre>

<div class="your-Turn">
  <h4><i class="fa fa-pencil" aria-hidden="true"></i> Your turn</h4>
  <ol>
    <li>In your <code><%= '<head>' %></code>, on a new line right after the <code><%= '</title>' %></code> line, add the <code><%= '<style>' %></code> block from the example above. (Copying it is allowed &mdash; even professionals copy CSS!)</li>
    <li>Now the fun part: swap <code>lightskyblue</code> for another color and watch the preview. Try <code>lightpink</code>, <code>palegreen</code>, <code>lavender</code>, <code>moccasin</code>, or even <code>black</code>.</li>
    <li>Found your color? Click <strong>Check My Work</strong>.</li>
  </ol>
</div>

<div class="bonus-Box">
  <h4>Going further with color</h4>
  <p>Browsers understand about 140 color names &mdash; see <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/named-color" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the full list on MDN</a>. And try adding a second rule inside the curly braces: <code>color: white;</code> changes the <em>text</em> color. There's a whole world of CSS waiting after this tutorial.</p>
</div>

<script>
  function lessonCheck(doc, html) {
    if(missingClosingTag(html, 'style'))
      return {ok: false, message: 'Your ' + codeSample('<style>') + ' element is missing its closing ' + codeSample('</style>') + ' tag &mdash; without it, the browser thinks the rest of your page is CSS!'}

    var styles = doc.querySelectorAll('style')

    if(styles.length == 0)
      return {ok: false, message: 'I don&rsquo;t see a ' + codeSample('<style>') + ' element yet. Copy the example block into your ' + codeSample('<head>') + ', right after the title line.'}

    var css = ''
    for(var i = 0; i < styles.length; i++)
      css += styles[i].textContent + '\n'

    if(!/background(-color)?\s*:/i.test(css)) {
      if(/background(-color)?\s+[a-z#]/i.test(css))
        return {ok: false, message: 'So close &mdash; don&rsquo;t forget the colon! It should be ' + codeSample('background-color: lightskyblue;')}
      return {ok: false, message: 'Your style element is there, but I don&rsquo;t see a background rule inside it yet. Add ' + codeSample('body { background-color: lightskyblue; }')}
    }

    if(!/background(-color)?\s*:\s*[^;\s}]/i.test(css))
      return {ok: false, message: 'Your background rule needs a color after the colon, like ' + codeSample('background-color: lavender;')}

    return {ok: true, message: 'A fresh coat of paint! Your page is one of a kind now.'}
  }
</script>
